properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense Pacific weather system is currently approaching the North Coast. Strong southeast winds have developed and will eventually reach speeds of 80 to 100 km/hr along the North Coast and Haida Gwaii early this morning. The southeast winds will shift to southwest winds this afternoon. The southwest winds will be generally 30 to 50 km/hr but gusts up to 70 are possible. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-09-28T01:59:04-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-09-27T11:37:04-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2417329622.2020
Area: Haida Gwaii, North Coast - coastal sections
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense Pacific weather system will bring rain to the North Coast beginning early this morning. The rain will intensify today as the system moves over the region. By Monday morning, rainfall amounts across the inland regions of the North Coast will vary from 50 to 70 mm. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-09-28T03:35:42-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-09-27T11:36:42-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1348744992.2020
Area: North Coast - inland including Terrace, North Coast - inland including Kitimat, North Coast - inland including Stewart
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A deep Gulf of Alaska low will make landfall over the Alaska coast early Monday morning, sending a strong frontal system across the Yukon. South to southwest winds of 40 to 60 km/h with gusts to 80 to 90 will develop overnight and early Monday morning over the South Klondike Highway, the Haines Road and the town of Haines Junction. Over the South Klondike Highway the strongest winds will occur near White Pass. Over the Haines Road the strongest winds will be north of Chilkat Pass and near the town of Haines junction. Winds will start to ease late Monday afternoon or early Monday evening. ### High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2020-09-28T16:36:35-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-09-28T00:37:35-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2509325957.2020
Area: Haines Road - Haines Junction to Pleasant Camp, South Klondike Highway - Carcross to White Pass, Haines Junction
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Easterly winds of 80 km/h will prevail near the Richardson Mountains tonight. The winds will cause localized blowing snow and limited visibilities overnight. Winds are forecast to ease overnight or early Monday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. An intense Pacific weather system will continue to spread heavy rain to the north coast. By Monday morning, storm total rainfall amounts across the coastal regions of the north coast will reach about 100 mm. The rain will taper off to a few showers on Monday morning as the system weakens. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Frost Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Frost may damage some crops in frost-prone areas. A ridge of high pressure will bring clearing skies and light winds allowing temperatures to drop below the freezing mark tonight over western Saskatchewan. ### Frost advisories are issued when temperatures are expected to reach the freezing mark during the growing season, leading to potential damage and destruction to plants and crops. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
